1 A RESOLUTION recognizing March 2025 to be Kentucky Maternal and Infant
2 Mortality and Disparities Awareness Month.
3 WHEREAS, economic inequality, structural racism, and public health failures have
4 resulted in higher illness and death rates for black people, especially when it comes to
5 maternal and reproductive health; and
6 WHEREAS, Kentucky is suffering a maternal mortality crisis as a result of
7 underinvesting and underfunding in health care for women, particularly in black
8 communities, leading to a precipitous increase in maternal mortality rates and racial
9 disparities; and
10 WHEREAS, data shows a racial disparity exists among the maternal mortality rate
11 in black women and white women in the United States, as the maternal mortality rate for
12 black women is 55.3 per 100,000 compared to white women who have a maternal
13 mortality rate of 19.1 per 100,000 live births; and
14 WHEREAS, black women are estimated to be three to four times more likely to die
15 from a pregnancy-related complication than white women; and
16 WHEREAS, the incidence of pregnancy-related mortality of black women in some
17 parts of the United States is close to that of women in some developing countries; and
18 WHEREAS, it is estimated more than 60 percent of pregnancy-related deaths are
19 preventable; and
20 WHEREAS, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC),
21 the leading causes of infant mortality are birth defects, low birthweight and preterm birth,
22 maternal pregnancy complications, sudden infant death syndrome, and unintentional
23 injuries; and
24 WHEREAS, the national infant mortality rate for white infants is 5.4 per 1,000 live
25 births and the national infant mortality rate for black infants is more than double at an
26 alarming rate of 10.6 per 1,000 live births; and
27 WHEREAS, the infant mortality rate for black infants was 9.9 per 1,000 births
