2 WHEREAS, the leading cause of infant mortality in Kentucky is prematurity-
3 related conditions followed by sudden unexpected infant death syndrome; and
4 WHEREAS, black infants are 2.3 times more likely to die from complications
5 related to low birthweight compared to white infants; and black mothers are 2.5 times
6 more likely than white mothers to receive late or no prenatal care; and
7 WHEREAS, in the United States, the rate of preterm birth among black women is
8 36 percent higher than the rate of preterm birth among white women; and
9 WHEREAS, to reduce health disparities, policymakers could improve maternal
10 health outcomes and lower infant mortality by providing equity in care to all people in
11 Kentucky, including helping patients manage chronic conditions such as diabetes, heart
12 disease, high blood pressure, and obesity; identifying and addressing unconscious bias in
13 healthcare; and ensuring all pregnant women have adequate access to perinatal and
14 postpartum care;
15 NOW, THEREFORE,
16 Be it resolved by the House of Representatives of the General Assembly of the
17 Commonwealth of Kentucky:
